<B><FONT SIZE=+2>The Manchester Multimedia Information System</FONT></B>
<BR>&nbsp;

<P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Data Model</FONT></B>
<BR>&nbsp;
<UL>
<LI>
a new feature/image added incrementally</LI>

<LI>
image attributes depend on the appliction, interpretation algorithms, etc...</LI>

<LI>
uses the multi-layered, semantic net (figure p.379)</LI>

<LI>
uses domain knowledge to automatically relate an image to a domain object</LI>
</UL>
Each&nbsp; image is characterized by:
<UL>
<LI>
raw image with unique id</LI>

<LI>
interpretation date, compression tech.</LI>

<LI>
a set of feature attributes (height, width, number of images, etc...)</LI>

<LI>
a set of<B> B</B>asic <B>L</B>ogical <B>O</B>bjec<B>T</B>s derived from
the image</LI>

<LI>
a set of relative structural and spatial relationships among blots</LI>
</UL>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Content Similarity Retrieval</FONT>

<P>Classification of the object and the structural relationships of the
images' objects

<P><B>Image Object Classifications</B>

<P>Use an algorithm to classify objects

<P><B>Classification and Spatial Relationship Score</B>

<P>They are used to compute the "confidence sore" which is used during
retrieval
<BR>&nbsp;

<P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Query Languages and User Interface</FONT></B>

<P>Queries can be formulated by expressions on data types, structures,
and content.

<P><B>Query by example</B>:&nbsp; use an image or blot and specify the
attribute match.&nbsp; Images/Blots of these attributes matches will be
returned.

<P>Results and Query Refinement
<UL>
<LI>
results are ranked and listed</LI>

<LI>
results can be named and saved for later usage</LI>
</UL>

